## 2. PLATFORM: SwiftUI (iOS)

**Target:**
Swift 6
iOS 17+
Xcode 16+

Prefer iOS 18 APIs when deployment target allows.

**Structure** (match if it already exists; otherwise propose this):
```
Sources/App/ | Views/{Feature}/ | ViewModels/ | Models/ | Services/{Network,Persistence}/ | Utilities/ | Resources/ | Tests/
```

**Use:** `@Observable` (Observation framework, not legacy `ObservableObject` unless the project already uses it), `async/await`, structured concurrency (`TaskGroup`, not detached tasks without reason), `NavigationStack` (never `NavigationView` — it's deprecated), `@State`/`@Binding`/`@Environment` for state, SF Symbols, native `Codable` for JSON unless project already uses a different layer.

**Concurrency correctness (common bug source — verify every time):**
- UI-touching code is `@MainActor`. Don't sprinkle `@MainActor` everywhere defensively — only where it's actually needed (ViewModels that publish to UI, not pure data layers).
- Never call `async` work directly in a View body; use `.task {}` or a ViewModel method triggered from `.onAppear`/`.task`.
- Avoid retain cycles in closures capturing `self` inside long-lived async/Combine chains — use `[weak self]` when the closure outlives the call site.

**Avoid:** `NavigationView`, massive single-file Views (>250 lines — extract subviews), force-unwraps (`!`) on anything from network/user input, business logic inside `body`.

**Localization mechanism:** String Catalogs (`.xcstrings`) or `.strings` files — never inline literal strings in Views.

---

## 3. PLATFORM: React Native (Expo)

**Target:** Latest stable Expo SDK + React Native. TypeScript only — no `.js` files for new code. Functional components + hooks only, no class components.

**Structure:**
```
src/components/ | screens/ | navigation/ | hooks/ | services/ | utils/ | assets/
```

**Use:** React Navigation for routing, Expo SecureStore for secrets/tokens (never AsyncStorage for sensitive data), Expo Notifications, `React.memo`/`useMemo`/`useCallback` deliberately (not on every component — only where a measured or obvious re-render cost exists), `FlatList`/`FlashList` for any list, never `.map()` inside a `ScrollView` for dynamic-length data.

Prefer Expo first-party APIs over third-party packages whenever equivalent functionality exists.

**Common bug sources — check every time:**
- `useEffect` dependency arrays are complete and correct — missing deps cause stale closures; this is the #1 RN bug source. Don't suppress the lint rule without a one-line comment explaining why.
- Async state updates after unmount: guard with a cleanup flag or abort controller, especially in `useEffect` fetches.
- Navigation params are typed (TypeScript generics on the navigator), not loosely typed `any`.
- Platform-specific code (`Platform.OS` checks) only where behavior genuinely differs — don't branch needlessly.

**Avoid:** class components, inline anonymous functions passed as props to list items (causes re-renders — define with `useCallback` or hoist out), heavy synchronous work on the JS thread (use `InteractionManager` or move to a worker if truly heavy).

**Localization mechanism:** Expo Localization + i18next (or the project's existing i18n library) — never inline literal strings in JSX.

---

## 4. PLATFORM: Jetpack Compose (Android)

**Target:** Kotlin 2+, latest stable Compose BOM, Material 3.

**Structure:**
```
data/ | domain/ | presentation/ | di/ | utils/
```

**Use:** MVVM with `ViewModel` + `StateFlow` (expose `StateFlow`, not mutable state, from ViewModel to UI), `SharedFlow` for one-off events (navigation, snackbars), Hilt for DI, Compose Navigation, `remember`/`derivedStateOf` for expensive derived state, stable/immutable data classes for UI state (`@Immutable`/`@Stable` annotations where appropriate).

Prefer `collectAsStateWithLifecycle()` when lifecycle-runtime-compose is available.

**Common bug sources — check every time:**
- Unstable parameter types (mutable lists, lambdas recreated each recomposition) cause unnecessary recomposition — prefer `ImmutableList` or wrap with `remember` for lambdas passed deep into the tree.
- State hoisting: Composables that need to be reusable take state + callbacks as parameters, they don't own mutable state internally unless they're truly leaf/private.
- `LaunchedEffect` keys are correct — a wrong/missing key either re-runs too often or not when it should.
- Don't collect `Flow`/`StateFlow` with `collectAsState()` deep in nested composables when it could be hoisted once — avoids redundant collection.

**Avoid:** business logic inside `@Composable` functions, giant composables (extract), unstable lambda allocation inside hot-path composables, `LiveData` for new code (use `StateFlow`) unless the project already standardizes on `LiveData`.

**Localization mechanism:** `strings.xml` resources + `stringResource()` — never inline literal strings in Composables.

---

## 5. PLATFORM: Flutter

**Target:** Latest stable Flutter + Dart, Material 3, sound null safety.

**Structure:**
```
lib/core/ | features/{feature}/{data,domain,presentation}/ | l10n/ | main.dart
```

**Use:** BLoC (or the pattern already in the project — don't introduce BLoC into a Provider/Riverpod project without asking) for state management, GetIt for service location, GoRouter for navigation, `const` constructors everywhere possible, `ListView.builder`/`GridView.builder` for any dynamic-length list (never a non-lazy `Column` of many children).

If the project already uses Riverpod, Provider, Cubit, or another state-management solution, continue using the existing approach instead of introducing BLoC.

**Common bug sources — check every time:**
- Missing `const` on widgets that don't depend on changing state — direct cause of unnecessary rebuilds; add it by default unless the widget genuinely depends on runtime values.
- `BuildContext` used after an `await` without checking `context.mounted` first — causes crashes on disposed widgets. Always guard.
- Keys (`ValueKey`/`UniqueKey`) on list items when the list can reorder/delete — missing keys cause state to leak between items.
- BLoC: events and states are immutable (`Equatable` or `freezed`); don't mutate state in place.

**Avoid:** massive build methods (extract widgets), business logic inside `build()`, rebuilding the whole tree when only a leaf needs to update (scope `BlocBuilder`/`Consumer` narrowly).

**Localization mechanism:** `intl` package + ARB files under `l10n/` — never inline literal strings in widgets.

---

## 5.5 AI Code Generation Rules

Always:

- Generate complete working code.
- Include all required imports.
- Include models, ViewModels, repositories, and services when needed.
- Include loading, empty, and error states.
- Preserve existing comments.
- Avoid placeholder implementations.
- Avoid pseudocode.
- State assumptions explicitly if backend contracts are unknown.

## 6. FINAL CHECKLIST (self-check before returning code — don't re-read this whole file, just run this list)

- [ ] Operating Mode correctly identified (DEV / REVIEW / REFACTOR / EXECUTE) and followed
- [ ] Matches detected platform only, existing project structure respected
- [ ] No duplicated logic; existing file edited where sensible vs. new file justified
- [ ] Business logic outside UI layer
- [ ] Loading / empty / error states present
- [ ] Accessibility labels + dynamic text + dark mode respected
- [ ] No hardcoded user-facing strings; localization mechanism used; RTL respected
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets; input validated; HTTPS only
- [ ] Lists are lazy/virtualized; no main-thread blocking work
- [ ] New dependency (if any) justified in one sentence
- [ ] Network/async errors handled distinctly, not swallowed
- [ ] Platform-specific bug checklist (§2–5) reviewed for the relevant platform
- [ ] Unit tests added for new business logic
- [ ] No pseudocode, no missing imports, no silent omissions
- [ ] (REVIEW/REFACTOR modes only) Report uses P0–P3 classification; no code changed without approval

